--Why async/await Was Introduced

Before async/await, JavaScript handled asynchronous operations mainly using:

Callbacks → led to callback hell
Promises → better, but still chained and sometimes hard to read

getData()
  .then(data => processData(data))
  .then(result => saveResult(result))
  .catch(err => handleError(err));
Even though promises improved things, complex flows still became hard to follow.

Solution: async/await was introduced to make async code look
like synchronous code, improving readability and maintainability.

Please note - async/await is just syntactic sugar over Promises
This means:

It doesn’t replace promises
It simply provides a cleaner way to write them



--How async functions work

An async function:
Always returns a Promise
Wraps return values automatically in a resolved Promise
An async function is just a normal JavaScript function with a special behavior:
It ALWAYS returns a Promise, no matter what you return inside it.

Step-by-step understanding
Case 1: Returning a normal value
async function example() {
  return "Hello";
}
What you might think:

👉 It returns "Hello"

What actually happens:

👉 It returns a Promise that resolves to "Hello"

So internally, it's like:

function example() {
  return Promise.resolve("Hello");
}
How to see this in action
async function example() {
  return "Hello";
}

console.log(example());
Output:
Promise { "Hello" }
To get the actual value

You must use .then() or await:

example().then(result => console.log(result));

✔ Output:

Hello
Case 2: Returning a Promise manually
async function example() {
  return Promise.resolve("Hi");
}
What happens?

👉 JavaScript does NOT wrap it twice

It just returns the same Promise.

Case 3: Throwing an error
async function example() {
  throw "Something went wrong";
}
What happens?

👉 This becomes a rejected Promise

Equivalent to:

function example() {
  return Promise.reject("Something went wrong");
}
Big Rule (Very Important)

Inside an async function:

You write	JavaScript converts it to
return value	Promise.resolve(value)
throw error	Promise.reject(error)


Now let’s add await (how execution works)
async function test() {
  console.log("Step 1");

  let data = await Promise.resolve("Step 2");

  console.log(data);

  console.log("Step 3");
}

test();
Execution Flow
Step 1
(wait happens here)
Step 2
Step 3
What’s really happening:
Function starts
Runs until it hits await
Pauses the function
Waits for Promise to resolve
Continues execution
Important Clarification 🚨

👉 await does NOT block the whole program
👉 It only pauses that async function

Example:

async function test() {
  console.log("A");
  await Promise.resolve();
  console.log("B");
}

console.log("Start");
test();
console.log("End");
Output:
Start
A
End
B

✔ This proves JavaScript is still non-blocking



imple Analogy

Think of an async function like ordering food:

You place an order 🍔
You wait (await)
When food arrives → continue eating

But while waiting:
👉 Other people (other code) keep doing their work




Async makes a function return a Promise automatically
return → becomes Promise.resolve()
throw → becomes Promise.reject()
await pauses execution inside the function only until the promise resolves.
Await Can only be used inside async functions
The rest of JavaScript keeps running normally

--Error handling with async code
Use try...catch instead of .catch()
async function getData() {
  try {
    let data = await Promise.reject("Error occurred");
    console.log(data);
  } catch (error) {
    console.log(error);
  }
}

--Comparison with Promises
Using Promises:
fetchData()
  .then(data => process(data))
  .then(result => console.log(result))
  .catch(err => console.log(err));

using async/await
async function handleData() {
  try {
    const data = await fetchData();
    const result = process(data);
    console.log(result);
  } catch (err) {
    console.log(err);
  }
}

Less chaining
Cleaner structure
Easier debugging


Async/await does not replace Promises:
It is built on top of Promises
You can still use .then() if needed
async function example() {
  return 42;
}


internally it is
function example() {
  return Promise.resolve(42);
}

Simple Example (Real-world style)
function delay(ms) {
  return new Promise(resolve => setTimeout(resolve, ms));
}
async function run() {
  console.log("Start");
  await delay(1000);
  console.log("After 1 second");
}

run();

Key Takeaways
delay() creates a Promise that resolves after time
await pauses only the async function
JavaScript remains non-blocking
Execution resumes after Promise resolves
